Abstract: Manipulation in immersive virtual environments is difficult partly because we humans must do without the haptic contact with real objects we rely on in the real world to orient ourselves and our manipulanda. To compensate for this lack, we propose exploiting the real objects one does have in a virtual environment, one's own body parts. We present a unified framework for virtual-environment interaction based on proprioception, a person's sense of the position and orientation of his body and limbs. We describe a taxonomy of three forms of body-relative interaction: Automatic scaling is a way to instantly bring objects within reach so that users can manipulate them using proprioceptive cues. Several novel virtual interaction techniques based upon automatic scaling and our proposed framework of proprioception allow a user to intuitively, efficiently, precisely, and lazily interact with a virtual world. Finally we describe the integration of these techniques into a real-world system: the Chapel Hill Immersive Modeling Program . C R C a t e g o r i e s a n d S u b j e c t D e s c r i p t o r s : I.3.6 [Computer Graphics]: Methodology and Techniques - Interaction Techniques; I.3.7 [Computer Graphics]: Three-Dimensional Graphics and Realism - Virtual Reality. A d d i t i o n a l K e y w o r d s : v i r t u a l w o r l d s , v i r t u a l environments, navigation, selection, manipulation. The promise of immersive virtual environments is one of a computer-generated three-dimensional environment in which a user can directly perceive and interact with three-dimensional virtual objects. The underlying belief motivating most virtual reality (VR) research is that this will lead to more natural and effective human-computer interfaces. Promising results in several key application domains have been demonstrated: It is interesting to note that many of the "successes" listed above fall within the realm of spatial visualization. The applications take advantage of the intuitive view specification (via head tracking) offered by most VR systems but have little to do with direct object manipulation within a virtual environment. Why is it difficult to do much more than look around in a virtual world? Limited input information: Most virtual-environment systems accept position and orientation (pose) data on the user's head and (if lucky) two hands. This is typically augmented by a button or glove to provide signal/event information. This suffices for specifying simple 6 degree of freedom (DOF) motion and placement. In the real world, we do this and much more: 
